          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>In the clinical case presented, what does the combination of ALT at 820 U/L and </p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>In the clinical case presented, what does the combination of ALT at 820 U/L and AST at 680 U/L with only mildly elevated alkaline phosphatase indicate?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Cholestatic liver injury from bile duct obstruction</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>In cholestasis, ALP and GGT rise sharply while transaminases remain only mildly elevated — the opposite of this patient's pattern.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Acute hepatocellular injury with widespread liver cell damage</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. ALT and AST rising dramatically (10–100× normal) with only mild ALP elevation defines the hepatocellular pattern, consistent with acute viral hepatitis.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Chronic liver disease with portal hypertension</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>In chronic liver disease, albumin falls and prothrombin time is markedly prolonged. This patient's normal albumin indicates preserved synthetic function.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Haemolytic anaemia with secondary liver involvement</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Haemolysis causes unconjugated (indirect) hyperbilirubinaemia. This patient has predominantly direct bilirubin elevation, pointing to hepatocyte pathology.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Review the two main LFT patterns: hepatocellular (ALT/AST >> ALP) versus cholestatic (ALP/GGT >> ALT/AST). This patient's transaminases at 800+ with ALP only mildly raised fits the hepatocellular pattern."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct! Massively elevated transaminases with mild ALP elevation is the hallmark hepatocellular pattern, pointing to direct liver cell damage as seen in acute viral hepatitis."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
