        {
          "duration": {
            "from": 250.35000000000002,
            "to": 260.35
          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>A rise in unconjugated (indirect) bilirubin with normal conjugated (direct) bili</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>A rise in unconjugated (indirect) bilirubin with normal conjugated (direct) bilirubin suggests pathology at which level?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>At the hepatocyte level, indicating liver cell necrosis</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Hepatocyte necrosis causes conjugated (direct) bilirubin to rise because the liver processes bilirubin but cannot excrete it through damaged bile canaliculi.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Beyond the hepatocyte, indicating bile duct obstruction</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Bile duct obstruction raises conjugated (direct) bilirubin — bilirubin has already been conjugated but cannot flow into the duodenum.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Before the hepatocyte, indicating pre-hepatic causes such as haemolysis</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Unconjugated bilirubin accumulates when excess bilirubin is produced (haemolysis) or conjugation is impaired (Gilbert's syndrome) — both upstream of hepatic processing.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>In the kidney, indicating impaired bilirubin excretion</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The kidney does not play a primary role in bilirubin metabolism. Bilirubin is conjugated in the liver and excreted via bile into the intestine.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Think of bilirubin flowing through a sequence: production → conjugation in the hepatocyte → excretion via bile. Unconjugated bilirubin rises with upstream problems; conjugated bilirubin rises with downstream problems."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct! Unconjugated bilirubin rises with pre-hepatic causes — haemolysis and Gilbert's syndrome are the commonest examples in Indian clinical practice."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
