          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>Which pattern of thyroid function test results indicates secondary hypothyroidis</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Which pattern of thyroid function test results indicates secondary hypothyroidism due to pituitary failure?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>High TSH with low free T4</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>This indicates primary hypothyroidism — the thyroid itself is failing, so the pituitary raises TSH to compensate. The feedback loop is intact.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Low TSH with high free T4</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>This indicates primary hyperthyroidism (e.g., Graves' disease). Excess thyroid hormone suppresses TSH through negative feedback.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Low TSH with low free T4</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. When the pituitary fails, it cannot produce adequate TSH, so the thyroid is understimulated and free T4 falls. This is why TSH alone is insufficient when pituitary disease is suspected.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>High TSH with normal free T4</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>This is subclinical hypothyroidism — the pituitary senses marginally low thyroid hormone and raises TSH, but free T4 remains within the normal range.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Recall the four patterns: primary hypo (↑TSH, ↓T4), primary hyper (↓TSH, ↑T4), secondary hypo (↓TSH, ↓T4), and subclinical hypo (↑TSH, normal T4). Secondary means the fault is at the pituitary level."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct! In secondary hypothyroidism, the pituitary cannot produce TSH, so the thyroid is understimulated. Both TSH and free T4 are low — always request free T4 alongside TSH when pituitary disease is suspected."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
