          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>What is the most common cause of hyperthyroidism?</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>What is the most common cause of hyperthyroidism?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Hashimoto's thyroiditis</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Hashimoto's is the most common cause of hypothyroidism, not hyperthyroidism. Anti-TPO antibodies progressively destroy the gland, reducing hormone output.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Graves' disease</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Graves' disease is the commonest cause of hyperthyroidism. TSH receptor antibodies mimic TSH and drive uncontrolled thyroid hormone production.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Iodine deficiency</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Iodine deficiency causes hypothyroidism, not hyperthyroidism. In pregnancy, severe deficiency leads to cretinism with intellectual disability.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Toxic thyroid nodule</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>A toxic nodule can cause hyperthyroidism through autonomous hormone production, but Graves' disease accounts for the majority of cases overall.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Remember: Hashimoto's → commonest cause of hypothyroidism (destruction); Graves' → commonest cause of hyperthyroidism (stimulation). Both are autoimmune but have opposite effects."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct! Graves' disease causes hyperthyroidism through stimulating TSH receptor antibodies, featuring tremor, palpitations, exophthalmos, and pretibial myxoedema."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
